# Rails 2.0: The Evolution Fork

**Shifting the focus from bookkeeping to strategic thinking.**

Welcome to the Rails Evolution Fork. Originally branching from the dormant `Rails-18xx` repository, this project represents a massive 6-month, 100,000+ line architectural rewrite. The core objective: upgrade the engine from a static, manual ledger into a dynamic, living ecosystem capable of supporting synchronous, championship-level competitive play. 

By drastically reducing cognitive load and visual strain, a full game of 1835 can now be played in two hours instead of three—with absolute stability and zero UI jitter.

📺 **[See the Engine, UI, and AI in action on YouTube: 18xxEvolution](https://www.youtube.com/@18xxEvolution)**

---

## 🧠 1. The Native AI Engine
The decision logic has been completely decoupled to build an autonomous "brain." This is not a simple heuristic bot; it is a hybrid engine designed for human interaction, AI building assistance, and headless dry-run simulations.

* **Data-Driven "Opening Books":** The AI loads external JSON strategy files to guide draft picks and opening moves based on historical performance and asset synergy, mimicking human variation rather than rigid rules.
* **Dry-Run Simulations:** Utilizes the `RevenueAdapter` to spin up parallel network graphs, allowing the AI to simulate and score potential tile lays before committing to a move.
* **AI Building Assistant:** In-game, the AI can be invoked to instantly calculate and build the tile that maximizes current train income—an invaluable tool for training and game testing.
* **Variable Action Resolution:** When humans negotiate variable-priced train trades, the AI automatically unpacks the slider into discrete, scorable fixed-price actions to evaluate its own bids.

## 🖥️ 2. The UI, UX, and Cognitive Load Revolution
The interface has been completely overhauled to create a rock-steady environment. There is now a single source of truth for all information, eliminating duplicated and cluttered text.

* **Railcards:** The tactile board game experience is back. Certificates (privates, shares, trains) are physical-looking beige "Railcards." When actionable, they become highlighted buttons matching a strict global color scheme (Red = Sell, Green = Buy, Blue = Action). When transferred, they physically animate across the screen.
* **The Linear OR Panel:** The old, cluttered OR panel is gone. It is replaced by a strict, top-to-bottom linear sequence (Build > Marker > Revenue > Buy > Special). Inactive steps are grayed out, so players always know exactly where they are in the sequence.
